But since `I` is a direct sum decomposition, we know that `I` itself is independent. The definition of independence for `I` means that for any finite subset `J` of `I`, the sum `∑ p in J, p` is direct. The key insight is that a direct sum decomposition at the level of the whole module `M` implies directness for any finite collection of its submodules at any point `c`.

To prove the second part (supremum at `c` is `M c`):
We need to show that `∑ p in I, p.val c = M c`.
The definition of `DirectSumDecomposition` says that `sSup I = ⊤` (where `sSup` is the supremum in the lattice of submodules). The supremum of a set of submodules is the sum of all vectors in any of them. So, `sSup I = M` as a set.
At the point `c`, we need to show that `∑ p in I, p.val c = M c`. This follows from the fact that `sSup I = M` and how `sSup` interacts with pointwise operations. Specifically, `sSup pointwise = pointwise sSup` when the latter is well-defined. Since `sSup I = ⊤` (the top element in the lattice of submodules, which is the whole module `M`), we have `sSup (fun p : I ↦ p.val c) = ⊤`, which means `∑ p in I, p.val c = M c`.

